<p>Tennessee's economy is remarkably diverse given its mid-South position. Nashville has transformed from a country music capital into a major healthcare industry hub -- nearly a third of the investor-owned hospital companies in the United States are headquartered in Nashville, including HCA Healthcare (one of the country's largest hospital operators) and Community Health Systems. The music and entertainment industry anchors a tourism economy that draws over 16 million visitors annually to Nashville alone. Tennessee's automotive manufacturing footprint has expanded dramatically with the Volkswagen plant in Chattanooga, the Ford Blue Oval City EV campus under construction near Memphis, and dozens of suppliers throughout the state. FedEx is headquartered in Memphis, reflecting Tennessee's significance as a logistics hub straddling the Mississippi River.</p>

<p>Tennessee completed a long process of eliminating state income tax when the Hall Income Tax -- which taxed investment income like dividends and interest, but never wages -- was fully repealed effective January 1, 2021. Tennessee workers have never paid a state income tax on wages, and since 2021, there is now no Tennessee state income tax at all. Your Tennessee pay stub shows only federal deductions. This generator calculates all federal taxes correctly and downloads as a professional PDF.</p>

<h2>Tennessee Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Tennessee has a 0% state income tax on all income, including wages, salaries, and investment income. The Hall Income Tax, which existed since 1929 and applied to dividend and interest income (not wages), was phased out beginning in 2016 and fully repealed on January 1, 2021. Tennessee joins Florida, Texas, Nevada, Washington, Wyoming, South Dakota, Alaska, and New Hampshire as states with no personal income tax.</p>

<p>Tennessee funds its government through the sales tax (7% state rate plus up to 2.75% local), one of the highest combined sales tax rates in the country. Tennessee also has significant excise taxes on alcohol, tobacco, and gasoline. None of these appear as payroll deductions.</p>

<p>On a Tennessee pay stub, deductions are entirely federal:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Federal income tax:</strong> IRS graduated brackets, 10% to 37%</li>
  <li><strong>Social Security:</strong> 6.2% up to the $168,600 wage base</li>
  <li><strong>Medicare:</strong> 1.45% of all wages</li>
  <li><strong>Voluntary deductions:</strong> Health insurance, 401(k), etc.</li>
</ul>

<p>The absence of state income tax makes Tennessee exceptionally attractive for higher earners relocating from states like California, New York, and Illinois. A Tennessee musician earning $300,000 avoids approximately $15,000 in California income tax annually, or approximately $20,000 in New York state and city taxes combined.</p>

<h2>Does Tennessee Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Tennessee does not have a state law requiring employers to provide pay stubs to employees. The Tennessee Wage Regulation Act focuses on when wages must be paid, not on the format or documentation of payment. There is no mandate for written wage statements under Tennessee state law for most private sector workers.</p>

<p>Federal FLSA record-keeping requirements apply, and essentially all major Tennessee employers provide electronic pay stubs through payroll systems. HCA Healthcare's thousands of employees access pay stubs through employee portals; FedEx workers use the company's payroll system; Volkswagen's Chattanooga plant provides detailed stubs reflecting UAW negotiated wages.</p>

<p>For independent contractors, gig workers, and cash-paid workers in Tennessee's large agricultural, construction, and service industries, this generator provides the income documentation needed for housing and financial applications.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Tennessee</h2>

<p>Without a state mandate, Tennessee pay stubs follow federal FLSA standards and employer best practice. A complete Tennessee pay stub should include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employer name and business address</li>
  <li>Employee name and identification</li>
  <li>Pay period start and end dates</li>
  <li>Pay date</li>
  <li>Total hours worked (hourly workers)</li>
  <li>Regular and overtime hours and rates</li>
  <li>Gross wages</li>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security tax withheld</li>
  <li>Medicare tax withheld</li>
  <li>Any voluntary deductions (401k, health insurance)</li>
  <li>Net pay</li>
  <li>Year-to-date totals</li>
</ul>

<p>Note the absence of any state income tax line on a Tennessee stub. This is correct -- there is no Tennessee income tax to withhold. Property managers and lenders in Tennessee understand this, but if submitting documentation to out-of-state parties, the absence of a state tax line should not raise concerns.</p>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Tennessee</h2>

<p>Tennessee law (TCA § 50-2-103) requires that wages be paid at least monthly. This monthly minimum is the same as several other states and reflects a general preference for minimal regulation. Most Tennessee employers pay bi-weekly or semi-monthly as a practical standard.</p>

<p>Tennessee requires that the regular payday be announced to employees in advance. If the regular payday falls on a non-business day (weekend or holiday), payment must be made on the preceding business day.</p>

<p>Tennessee does not have specific final paycheck timing requirements for involuntary termination -- the next regular payday is generally sufficient under state law. Federal law (FLSA) does require prompt payment, but Tennessee does not impose the strict same-day or within-72-hours requirements that California and some other states have.</p>

