<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Tennessee Workers</h2>

<h3>My pay stub shows no state income tax. Is that correct for Tennessee?</h3>
<p>Yes, completely correct. Tennessee has no state income tax on wages. The Hall Income Tax was fully repealed January 1, 2021, and Tennessee never taxed wage income even when the Hall Tax existed (it only taxed interest and dividend income). Your Tennessee pay stub correctly shows $0.00 in state income tax withholding. The only taxes on a Tennessee wage earner's stub are federal income tax, Social Security, and Medicare. Anyone who tells you that you should see Tennessee state income tax on your stub is mistaken.</p>

<h3>I'm a Nashville musician with irregular income. How do I generate pay stubs for apartment applications?</h3>
<p>Generate stubs for each pay period (weekly, bi-weekly, or monthly) reflecting your actual earnings during that period. For session work, the session fee is the gross pay for the period in which you received payment. For music publishing royalties or streaming payments, use the date received as the pay date. Nashville landlords, particularly in the Midtown and East Nashville markets, are accustomed to musicians' income patterns. Providing 3-6 months of stubs alongside bank statements that confirm deposits is the strongest documentation approach for variable income. Our <a href="/self-employed-pay-stub-generator">self-employed pay stub generator</a> has more detail on documenting irregular income streams.</p>

<h3>Tennessee has some of the highest sales tax in the country. Does that affect payroll?</h3>
<p>Tennessee's high sales tax (up to 9.75% combined state and local) does not affect payroll at all -- sales tax is paid by consumers at point of purchase and by retailers to the state government. It does not appear on pay stubs or affect employer withholding obligations. The high sales tax does affect workers' effective disposable income (you pay more on purchases), but that is separate from payroll documentation. Tennessee workers who move from no-sales-tax states like Oregon or Montana may need to adjust their personal budgets, but their pay stub deductions are limited to federal taxes.</p>

<h3>I work at the Volkswagen plant in Chattanooga. How does UAW membership affect my pay stub?</h3>
<p>Following the successful UAW organizing vote at the Chattanooga plant in 2024, UAW dues will appear as a deduction on pay stubs for dues-paying union members. UAW dues are typically 1.44% of straight-time wages (the rate can vary by contract and local). These dues are deducted from post-tax wages -- they do not reduce your federal or state taxable income in the same way that pre-tax benefit deductions do. Your pay stub will show UAW dues as a separate voluntary/union deduction line. Workers have the right to opt out of full union membership while remaining covered by the union contract (under certain circumstances), and "agency fees" (a subset of dues) may apply in their place.</p>

<h3>Does Tennessee have paid family leave or disability insurance I should know about?</h3>
<p>Tennessee has no state-funded paid family leave or disability insurance program. There are no employee payroll deductions for these programs, and Tennessee workers have no access to state-provided benefits when they cannot work due to illness, disability, or new child care needs (beyond federal FMLA unpaid leave). Workers who need income replacement for these situations must rely on employer-provided benefits (PTO, short-term disability plans) or private insurance. Tennessee's lack of these programs is consistent with its minimal-government approach and no-income-tax stance, but it means Tennessee workers have less automatic protection than workers in states like California, New York, or New Jersey.</p>

